T1  - What if Alexander Hamilton had been Argentinean? A comparison of the early monetary experiences of Argentina and the United States
AU  - Bordo, Michael D.
AU  - Végh, Carlos A.
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 49
IS  - 3
SP  - 459
EP  - 494
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/04/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0304-3932(02)00100-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304393202001009
KW  - Inflation tax
KW  - War finance
KW  - Argentina
AB  - The contrast between the early nineteenth century Argentinean experience of high inflation and the American experience of low inflation is interpreted in terms of an optimal taxation model. It is argued that the two countries’ experiences diverged because of the different constraints they faced in financing wartime government expenditures. In the presence of frequent wars, ever-tightening access to foreign capital, and an inadequate tax base, Argentina's use of the inflation tax may be viewed as an optimal solution to its wartime problems. By contrast, with the exception of the Revolutionary War, the absence of such constraints in the United States required full-tax smoothing, with only a temporary use of the inflation tax during wartime. Such policies were embodied in Alexander Hamilton's fiscal package of 1790, which allowed the United States to bond-finance most subsequent wartime expenditures.
